answers.body_markdown:
`await` cannot be used on the top-level, it must be inside an async function. There is a common practice to solve this however, it is not recommended:

```js
(async function() {
  const response = await APIService.get(&#39;/endpoint&#39;, {});
  ...
}());

// or

(async function() {
  const response = await APIService.get(&#39;/endpoint&#39;, {});
  ...
}()).then(...);
```

There is a proposal to allow async imports on top level but it is still in stage 3.
You can read more on this topic in [this article][1]


  [1]: https://v8.dev/features/top-level-await

Async and Await are extensions of promises.They are actually built on top of promises.Await cannot be used outside an Async function.Remember these rules for asunc and await.

 1. You Must Use the await keyword only in closure that is declared with the async keyword.
 2. Inside of an async closure, if another async function is called with the await keyword, the next line will not run until that lineâ€™s promise has resolved.

    
     async function myFunc() {
      return 10;
    }
    
    myFunc().then(alert); //OUTPUT: 10

   


Async tells you that a promise will be returned, if promise is not returned javascript automatically puts it in the resolved part. Running myFunc().then() works because myFunc is returning a promise.If Async and await is nor working for you try writing a custom promise and see if it works.You can goto this link [Promise - JavaScript][1]


  [1]: https://javascript.info/promise-basics

